# General Mashup Coding Rules & Best Practices

## 1. Project Environment Constraints
- Framework: **Odin** (custom Angular 18)
- UI Library: **IDS Enterprise NG** (`ids-enterprise-ng@18.2.4`)
- Underlying jQuery controls: **IDS Enterprise 4.98.3**
- Node: 18+ required
- Package manager: **npm** (never yarn or pnpm unless explicitly asked)

---

## 2. File & Folder Conventions

### Naming
| Type               | Convention            | Example                          |
|--------------------|-----------------------|----------------------------------|
| Component folder   | kebab-case            | `customer-list/`                 |
| Component files    | `<name>.component.ts` | `customer-list.component.ts`     |
| Module files       | `<name>.module.ts`    | `customer-list.module.ts`        |
| Service files      | `<name>.service.ts`   | `customer-list.service.ts`       |
| Model/Interface    | `<name>.model.ts`     | `customer.model.ts`              |
| Template           | `<name>.component.html`| `customer-list.component.html`  |
| Styles             | `<name>.component.scss`| `customer-list.component.scss`  |

### One-responsibility rule
- Each component does ONE thing.
- Extract data-fetching logic into Services — never put HTTP calls in components.
- Extract reusable logic into utility functions in `src/app/utils/`.

---

## 3. TypeScript Rules

### General
- **Always** use TypeScript strict mode (`"strict": true` in tsconfig).
- **Never** use `any` — define proper interfaces or types.
- **Always** type function return values explicitly.
- Use `readonly` on properties that should not be mutated after initialization.
- Use `const` over `let`; avoid `var`.

### Interfaces & Models
```typescript
// ✅ Correct — strongly typed model
export interface Customer {
  readonly id: number;
  name: string;
  email: string;
  createdAt: Date;
}

// ❌ Wrong — using any
const customer: any = { id: 1 };
```

### Angular Component Skeleton
```typescript
import { Component, OnInit, OnDestroy, ViewChild, ChangeDetectionStrategy, ChangeDetectorRef } from '@angular/core';
import { Subject } from 'rxjs';
import { takeUntil } from 'rxjs/operators';

@Component({
  selector: 'app-my-component',
  templateUrl: './my-component.component.html',
  styleUrls: ['./my-component.component.scss'],
  changeDetection: ChangeDetectionStrategy.OnPush
})
export class MyComponent implements OnInit, OnDestroy {
  private readonly destroy$ = new Subject<void>();

  constructor(private readonly cdr: ChangeDetectorRef) {}

  ngOnInit(): void {
    // subscribe to observables with takeUntil(this.destroy$)
  }

  ngOnDestroy(): void {
    this.destroy$.next();
    this.destroy$.complete();
  }
}
```

---

## 4. Angular Rules

### Modules
- Every feature area has its own `NgModule`.
- Lazy-load feature modules where possible.
- Shared components go in a `SharedModule` — import it where needed.

### Services
- Mark services as `@Injectable({ providedIn: 'root' })` unless they need component-scoped instances.
- HTTP services use `HttpClient` — always return `Observable`, never `Promise` (unless bridging with `lastValueFrom`).
- Handle errors with `catchError` operator; never swallow errors silently.

### Observables & Subscriptions
- Always unsubscribe. Use the `takeUntil(this.destroy$)` pattern or `async` pipe.
- Never subscribe inside subscribe (flatten with `switchMap`, `mergeMap`, etc.).
- Use `async` pipe in templates whenever possible — it manages subscriptions automatically.

### Template Best Practices
- Use `trackBy` on all `*ngFor` directives.
- Avoid complex expressions in templates — compute values in TypeScript.
- Use `OnPush` change detection with `markForCheck()` for mutable data.

---

## 5. IDS Component Rules (Angular)

### Initialization
- IDS components **must not** be accessed before `ngAfterViewInit`.
- Use `@ViewChild` with `{ static: false }` (the default) for IDS component refs.

### Event handling
- Always type the event parameter — check the `.d.ts` for the exact payload type.
```typescript
// ✅ Correct — typed event payload
onRowActivated(event: SohoDataGridRowActivatedEvent): void {
  console.log(event.row, event.item);
}
```

### Columns setup for DataGrid
```typescript
// Always define columns as a class property
columns: SohoDataGridColumn[] = [
  { id: 'id',   name: 'ID',   field: 'id',    sortable: true },
  { id: 'name', name: 'Name', field: 'name',  sortable: true },
];
```

### BusyIndicator
- Show busy indicator before async operations:
```html
<soho-busy-indicator [activated]="isBusy"></soho-busy-indicator>
```

---

## 6. SCSS / Styling Rules

- Import IDS theme at the root `styles.scss` level — never per-component.
- Use IDS CSS custom properties for colors — never hardcode hex values.
- Component-specific overrides only when absolutely necessary.
- Follow BEM-lite naming for custom classes: `block__element--modifier`.
- Use `px`/`rem` consistently — avoid `em` for layout.

---

## 7. Accessibility Rules

- All interactive IDS components are accessible by default — do NOT disable their ARIA attributes.
- Always provide `aria-label` or `aria-labelledby` for icon-only buttons.
- Keyboard navigation must work for all interactive elements.
- Do not use `tabindex > 0`.

---

## 8. Error Handling

- Never let errors silently fail.
- Display user-facing errors using the IDS `soho-message` or `soho-toast` components.
- Log technical errors to the console in development (`isDevMode()`).

```typescript
import { isDevMode } from '@angular/core';

catchError((error: HttpErrorResponse) => {
  if (isDevMode()) {
    console.error('[MyService] Error:', error);
  }
  this.toastService.show({ title: 'Error', message: error.message, type: 'error' });
  return EMPTY;
})
```

---

## 9. Performance Rules

- Avoid calling functions in templates (they run on every change detection cycle).
- Memoize expensive computations with `getter` properties or pipes.
- Use `soho-datagrid` virtual scrolling for large datasets (set `virtualScroll: true` in grid options).
- Debounce search/filter inputs with `debounceTime(300)` before triggering API calls.

---

## 10. Code Quality & Review Checklist

Before considering any component done, verify:
- [ ] No `any` types
- [ ] Subscriptions properly unsubscribed
- [ ] IDS component API verified against `lib/<component>/*.d.ts`
- [ ] At least one HTML example from `scraped_components/<slug>/` consulted
- [ ] Accessibility attributes present on interactive elements
- [ ] `OnPush` change detection applied
- [ ] Loading/error states handled with IDS components
- [ ] No magic strings — use constants or enums
